data.content:
Here are the four breaking changes from **Microsoft.OpenApi v2.x** and how to fix each:

---

### 1. `OpenApiString` removed â†’ use `JsonNode`
```csharp
// Before
using Microsoft.OpenApi.Any;
param.Schema.Example = new OpenApiString("1.0");

// After
using System.Text.Json.Nodes;
param.Schema.Example = JsonNode.Parse("\"1.0\"");
```

### 2. `OpenApiSecurityScheme.Reference` replaced â†’ use `OpenApiSecuritySchemeReference`
```csharp
// Before
var oAuthScheme = new OpenApiSecurityScheme
{
    Reference = new OpenApiReference { Type = ReferenceType.SecurityScheme, Id = "oauth2" }
};

// After
var oAuthScheme = new OpenApiSecuritySchemeReference("oauth2", null);
```

### 3. Collections are now nullable
`operation.Parameters`, `operation.Responses`, etc. can be `null`. Add null guards:
```csharp
var param = operation.Parameters?.FirstOrDefault(p => p.Name == "api-version");
operation.Responses ??= new OpenApiResponses();
operation.Responses.TryAdd("401", new OpenApiResponse { Description = "Unauthorized" });
```

### 4. `OpenApiSchema.Nullable` removed
OpenAPI 3.1 uses JSON Schema's `type` array instead of `nullable`. Remove the `.Nullable = false` assignment â€” it no longer exists on the model. If you need to express nullability, manipulate the `Type` property (a JSON Schema type set) instead.

Remove the `using Microsoft.OpenApi.Any;` import (no longer needed) and add `using System.Text.Json.Nodes;`.
